# ReMA — Remote Machine Access

Execute commands across machines through a shared mount. All machines must mount the same data volume.

## Quick Reference

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `rema start <name>` | Start worker in current directory |
| `rema stop <name>` | Stop worker |
| `rema status <name>` | idle / busy / off |
| `rema run <name> -- <cmd>` | Sync: real-time output, wait for completion |
| `rema run <name> --async -- <cmd>` | Async: submit and return immediately |
| `rema log <name>` | Show latest job output |
| `rema list` | Show all machines and status |

## Usage

Before running commands, the remote machine must be registered:
```bash
# On remote machine, in the desired working directory:
rema start <name>
```

Then from any machine:
```bash
# Check status
rema status <name>

# Run command (sync, real-time output)
rema run <name> -- nvidia-smi
rema run <name> -- "cd project && python train.py"

# Run command (async, returns immediately)
rema run <name> --async -- "sleep 10 && python train.py"

# Check output of async job
rema log <name>
```

## Key Behaviors

- Commands execute in the directory where `rema start` was run
- Status may show `off` briefly after sync — shared mount latency is normal
- `rema list` checks all registered machines; `off` means worker is not running or heartbeat expired
- Each job gets a unique ID; use `rema log <name> <job_id>` for specific jobs

## Environment

Set via `~/.rema_config` or environment variable:

| Variable | Default | Description |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `REMA_DIR` | required | Shared directory path |
| `REMA_LOG_KEEP_DAYS` | `7` | Auto-delete old logs |
